# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: dds-protocol
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:dds-protocol/data-distribution-service] DDS addresses the real-time data exchange needs of applications within aerospace, defense, air-traffic control, autonomous vehicles, medical devices, robotics, power generation, simulation and testing, smart grid management, transportation systems, and other applications.
[src:dds-protocol/data-distribution-service] DDS is a networking middleware that simplifies complex network programming.
[src:dds-protocol/data-distribution-service] It implements a publish–subscribe pattern for sending and receiving data, events, and commands among the nodes.
[src:dds-protocol/data-distribution-service] Nodes that produce information (publishers) create "topics" (e.g., temperature, location, pressure) and publish "samples".
[src:dds-protocol/data-distribution-service] DDS delivers the samples to subscribers that declare an interest in that topic.
[src:dds-protocol/data-distribution-service] DDS handles transfer chores: message addressing, data marshalling and de-marshalling (so subscribers can be on different platforms from the publisher), delivery, flow control, retries, etc.
[src:dds-protocol/data-distribution-service] Any node can be a publisher, subscriber, or both simultaneously.
[src:dds-protocol/data-distribution-service] The DDS publish-subscribe model virtually eliminates complex network programming for distributed applications.
[src:dds-protocol/data-distribution-service] DDS supports mechanisms that go beyond the basic publish-subscribe model.
[src:dds-protocol/data-distribution-service] The key benefit is that applications that use DDS for their communications are decoupled.
[src:dds-protocol/data-distribution-service] Little design time needs be spent on handling their mutual interactions.
[src:dds-protocol/data-distribution-service] In particular, the applications never need information about the other participating applications, including their existence or locations.
[src:dds-protocol/data-distribution-service] DDS allows the user to specify quality of service (QoS) parameters to configure discovery and behavior mechanisms up-front.
[src:dds-protocol/data-distribution-service] By exchanging messages anonymously, DDS simplifies distributed applications and encourages modular, well-structured programs.
[src:dds-protocol/data-distribution-service] DDS also automatically handles hot-swapping redundant publishers if the primary fails.
[src:dds-protocol/data-distribution-service] Subscribers always get the sample with the highest priority whose data is still valid (that is, whose publisher-specified validity period has not expired).
[src:dds-protocol/data-distribution-service] It automatically switches back to the primary when it recovers, too.
[src:dds-protocol/data-distribution-service] Both proprietary and open-source software implementations of DDS are available.
[src:dds-protocol/data-distribution-service] These include application programming interfaces (APIs) and libraries of implementations in Ada, C, C++, C#, Java, Python, Scala, Lua, Pharo, Ruby, and Rust.
[src:dds-protocol/data-distribution-service] DDS vendors participated in interoperability demonstrations at the OMG Spring technical meetings from 2009 to 2013.
[src:dds-protocol/data-distribution-service] During demos, each vendor published and subscribed to each other's topics using a test suite called the shapes demo.
[src:dds-protocol/data-distribution-service] For example, one vendor publishes information about a shape and the other vendors can subscribe to the topic and display the results on their own shapes display.
[src:dds-protocol/data-distribution-service] Each vendor takes turns publishing the information and the other subscribe.
[src:dds-protocol/data-distribution-service] Two things made the demos possible: the DDS-I or Real-Time Publish-Subscribe (RTPS) protocol, and the agreement to use a common model.
[src:dds-protocol/data-distribution-service] In March 2009, three vendors demonstrated interoperability between the individual, independent products that implemented the OMG Real-time Publish-Subscribe protocol version 2.1 from January 2009.
[src:dds-protocol/data-distribution-service] The demonstration included the discovery of each other's publishers and subscribers on different OS Platforms (Microsoft Windows and Linux) and supported multicast and unicast network communications.
[src:dds-protocol/data-distribution-service] Development of the DDS specification started in 2001.
[src:dds-protocol/data-distribution-service] In 2004, the Object Management Group (OMG) published DDS version 1.0.
[src:dds-protocol/data-distribution-service] Version 1.1 was published in December 2005, 1.2 in January 2007, and 1.4 in April 2015.
[src:dds-protocol/data-distribution-service] DDS is covered by several US patents, among others.
[src:dds-protocol/data-distribution-service] Other related standards followed the initial core document.
[src:dds-protocol/data-distribution-service] The Real-time Publish-Subscribe Wire Protocol DDS Interoperability Wire Protocol Specification ensured that information published on a topic using one vendor's DDS implementation is consumable by one or more subscribers using the same or different vendor's DDS implementations.
[src:dds-protocol/data-distribution-service] Although the specification is targeted at the DDS community, its use is not limited.
[src:dds-protocol/data-distribution-service] Versions 2.0 was published in April 2008, version 2.1 in November 2010, 2.2 in September 2014, and 2.3 in May 2019.
[src:dds-protocol/data-distribution-service] DDS for Lightweight CCM (dds4ccm) offers an architectural pattern that separates the business logic from the non-functional properties.
[src:dds-protocol/data-distribution-service] A 2012 extension added support for streams.
[src:dds-protocol/data-distribution-service] A Java 5 Language PSM for DDS defined a Java 5 language binding, referred to as a Platform Specific Model (PSM) for DDS.
[src:dds-protocol/data-distribution-service] It specified only the Data-Centric Publish-Subscribe (DCPS) portion of the DDS specification; Additionally, it encompasses the DDS APIs introduced by DDS-XTypes and DDS-CCM.
[src:dds-protocol/data-distribution-service] DDS-PSM-Cxx defines the ISO/IEC C++ PSM language binding, referred to as a Platform Specific Model (PSM) for DDS.
[src:dds-protocol/data-distribution-service] It provides a new C++ API for programming DDS that is more natural to a C++ programmer.
[src:dds-protocol/data-distribution-service] The specification provides mappings for the application programming interface (API) specified in DDS-XTypes, and accessing quality of service (QoS) profiles specified in DDS-CCM.
[src:dds-protocol/data-distribution-service] Extensible and Dynamic Topic Types for DDS (DDS-XTypes) provided support for data-centric publish-subscribe communication where topics are defined with specific data structures.
[src:dds-protocol/data-distribution-service] To be *extensible*, DDS topics use data types defined before compile time and used throughout the DDS global data space.
[src:dds-protocol/data-distribution-service] This model is desirable when static type checking is useful.
[src:dds-protocol/data-distribution-service] A Unified Modeling Language (UML) profile specified DDS domains and topics to be part of analysis and design modeling.
[src:dds-protocol/data-distribution-service] This specification also defined how to publish and subscribe objects without first describing the types in another language, such as XML or OMG IDL.
[src:dds-protocol/data-distribution-service] An interface definition language (IDL) was specified in 2014 independently from the Common Object Request Broker Architecture (CORBA) specification chapter 3.
[src:dds-protocol/data-distribution-service] This IDL 3.5 was compatible with the CORBA 3 specification, but extracted as its own specification allowing it to evolve independently from CORBA.
[src:dds-protocol/data-distribution-service] Other protocols to be mentioned are: DDS-XRCE (DDS for eXtremely Resource Constrained Environments), this specification protocol allows the communication between devices of limited resources, like microcontroller for example and a DDS network.
[src:dds-protocol/data-distribution-service] It makes publishing and subscribing to topics via an intermediate service in a DDS domain possible and DDS-RPC (RPC Over DDS) which defines Remote Procedure Calls.
[src:dds-protocol/data-distribution-service] These provide a bidirectional request/reply communication and determine distributed services, and are detailed using a service interface.
[src:dds-protocol/data-distribution-service] It also supports both synchronous and asynchronous method invocation.
[src:dds-protocol/data-distribution-service] Starting with DDS version 1.4 in 2015, the optional DLRL layer was moved to a separate specification.
[src:dds-protocol/message-oriented-middleware] MOM allows application modules to be distributed over heterogeneous platforms and reduces the complexity of developing applications that span multiple operating systems and network protocols.
[src:dds-protocol/message-oriented-middleware] The middleware creates a distributed communications layer that insulates the application developer from the details of the various operating systems and network interfaces.
[src:dds-protocol/message-oriented-middleware] Application programming interfaces (APIs) that extend across diverse platforms and networks are typically provided by MOM.
[src:dds-protocol/message-oriented-middleware] This middleware layer allows software components (applications, servlets, and other components) that have been developed independently and might run on different networked platforms to interact with one another.
[src:dds-protocol/message-oriented-middleware] Applications distributed on different network nodes use the application interface to communicate.
[src:dds-protocol/message-oriented-middleware] In addition, by providing an administrative interface, this new, virtual system of interconnected applications can be made fault tolerant and secure.
[src:dds-protocol/message-oriented-middleware] MOM provides software elements that reside in all communicating components of a client/server architecture and typically support asynchronous calls between the client and server applications.
[src:dds-protocol/message-oriented-middleware] MOM reduces the involvement of application developers with the complexity of the master-slave nature of the client/server mechanism.
[src:dds-protocol/message-oriented-middleware] All these models make it possible for one software component to affect the behavior of another component over a network.
[src:dds-protocol/message-oriented-middleware] They are different in that RPC- and ORB-based middleware create systems of tightly coupled components, whereas MOM-based systems allow for a loose coupling of components.
[src:dds-protocol/message-oriented-middleware] In an RPC- or ORB-based system, when one procedure calls another, it must wait for the called procedure to return before it can do anything else.
[src:dds-protocol/message-oriented-middleware] In these mostly synchronous messaging models, the middleware functions partly as a super-linker, locating the called procedure on a network and using network services to pass function or method parameters to the procedure and then to return results.
[src:dds-protocol/message-oriented-middleware] Note that Object request brokers also support fully asynchronous messaging via oneway invocations.
[src:dds-protocol/message-oriented-middleware] Central reasons for using a message-based communications protocol include its ability to store (buffer), route, or transform messages while conveying them from senders to receivers.
[src:dds-protocol/message-oriented-middleware] Another advantage of messaging provider-mediated messaging between clients is that by adding an administrative interface, you can monitor and tune performance.
[src:dds-protocol/message-oriented-middleware] Client applications are thus effectively relieved of every problem except that of sending, receiving, and processing messages.
[src:dds-protocol/message-oriented-middleware] It is up to the code that implements the MOM system and up to the administrator to resolve issues like interoperability, reliability, security, scalability, and performance.
[src:dds-protocol/message-oriented-middleware] Using a MOM system, a client makes an API call to send a message to a destination managed by the provider.
[src:dds-protocol/message-oriented-middleware] The call invokes provider services to route and deliver the message.
[src:dds-protocol/message-oriented-middleware] Once it has sent the message, the client can continue to do other work, confident that the provider retains the message until a receiving client retrieves it.
[src:dds-protocol/message-oriented-middleware] The message-based model, coupled with the mediation of the provider, makes it possible to create a system of loosely coupled components.
[src:dds-protocol/message-oriented-middleware] MOM comprises a category of inter-application communication software that generally relies on asynchronous message-passing, as opposed to a request-response architecture.
[src:dds-protocol/message-oriented-middleware] In asynchronous systems, message queues provide temporary storage when the destination program is busy or not connected.
[src:dds-protocol/message-oriented-middleware] In addition, most asynchronous MOM systems provide persistent storage to back up the message queue.
[src:dds-protocol/message-oriented-middleware] This means that the sender and receiver do not need to connect to the network at the same time (asynchronous delivery), and problems with intermittent connectivity are solved.
[src:dds-protocol/message-oriented-middleware] It also means that should the receiver application fail for any reason, the senders can continue unaffected, as the messages they send will simply accumulate in the message queue for later processing when the receiver restarts.
[src:dds-protocol/message-oriented-middleware] Many message-oriented middleware implementations depend on a message queue system.
[src:dds-protocol/message-oriented-middleware] Some implementations permit routing logic to be provided by the messaging layer itself, while others depend on client applications to provide routing information or allow for a mix of both paradigms.
[src:dds-protocol/message-oriented-middleware] Some implementations make use of broadcast or multicast distribution paradigms.
[src:dds-protocol/message-oriented-middleware] In a message-based middleware system, the message received at the destination need not be identical to the message originally sent.
[src:dds-protocol/message-oriented-middleware] A MOM system with built-in intelligence can transform messages and route to match the requirements of the sender or of the recipient.
[src:dds-protocol/message-oriented-middleware] In conjunction with the routing and broadcast/multicast facilities, one application can send a message in its own native format, and two or more other applications may each receive a copy of the message in their own native format.
[src:dds-protocol/message-oriented-middleware] Many modern MOM systems provide sophisticated message transformation (or mapping) tools which allow programmers to specify transformation rules applicable to a simple GUI drag-and-drop operation.
[src:dds-protocol/message-oriented-middleware] The primary disadvantage of many message-oriented middleware systems is that they require an extra component in the architecture, the message transfer agent (message broker).
[src:dds-protocol/message-oriented-middleware] As with any system, adding another component can lead to reductions in performance and reliability, and can also make the system as a whole more difficult and expensive to maintain.
[src:dds-protocol/message-oriented-middleware] In addition, many inter-application communications have an intrinsically synchronous aspect, with the sender specifically wanting to wait for a reply to a message before continuing (see real-time computing and near-real-time for extreme cases).
[src:dds-protocol/message-oriented-middleware] Because message-based communication inherently functions asynchronously, it may not fit well in such situations.
[src:dds-protocol/message-oriented-middleware] That said, most MOM systems have facilities to group a request and a response as a single pseudo-synchronous transaction.
[src:dds-protocol/message-oriented-middleware] With a synchronous messaging system, the calling function does not return until the called function has finished its task.
[src:dds-protocol/message-oriented-middleware] In a loosely coupled asynchronous system, the calling client can continue to load work upon the recipient until the resources needed to handle this work are depleted and the called component fails.
[src:dds-protocol/message-oriented-middleware] Of course, these conditions can be minimized or avoided by monitoring performance and adjusting message flow, but this is work that is not needed with a synchronous messaging system.
[src:dds-protocol/message-oriented-middleware] The important thing is to understand the advantages and liabilities of each kind of system.
[src:dds-protocol/message-oriented-middleware] Each system is appropriate for different kinds of tasks.
[src:dds-protocol/message-oriented-middleware] Sometimes, a combination of the two kinds of systems is required to obtain the desired behavior.
[src:dds-protocol/message-oriented-middleware] Historically, there was a lack of standards governing the use of message-oriented middleware that has caused problems.
[src:dds-protocol/message-oriented-middleware] Most of the major vendors have their own implementations, each with its own application programming interface (API) and management tools.
[src:dds-protocol/message-oriented-middleware] One of the long-standing standards for message-oriented middleware is X/Open group's XATMI specification (Distributed Transaction Processing: The XATMI Specification) which standardizes API for interprocess communications.
[src:dds-protocol/message-oriented-middleware] Known implementations for this API is ATR Baltic's Enduro/X middleware and Oracle's Tuxedo.
[src:dds-protocol/message-oriented-middleware] The Advanced Message Queuing Protocol (AMQP) is an approved OASIS and ISO standard that defines the protocol and formats used between participating application components, so implementations are interoperable.
[src:dds-protocol/message-oriented-middleware] It also supports transaction management, queuing, distribution, security, management, clustering, federation and heterogeneous multi-platform support.
[src:dds-protocol/message-oriented-middleware] Java applications that use AMQP are typically written in Java JMS.
[src:dds-protocol/message-oriented-middleware] Other implementations provide APIs for C#, C++, PHP, Python, Ruby, and other programming languages.
[src:dds-protocol/message-oriented-middleware] The High Level Architecture (HLA IEEE 1516) is an Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers (IEEE) and Simulation Interoperability Standards Organization (SISO) standard for simulation interoperability.
[src:dds-protocol/message-oriented-middleware] It defines a set of services, provided through an API in C++ or Java.
[src:dds-protocol/message-oriented-middleware] The services offer publish/subscribe-based information exchange, based on a modular Federation Object Model.
[src:dds-protocol/message-oriented-middleware] There are also services for coordinated data exchange and time advance, based on logical simulation time, as well as synchronization points.
[src:dds-protocol/message-oriented-middleware] Additional services provide transfer of ownership, data distribution optimizations and monitoring and management of participating Federates (systems).
[src:dds-protocol/message-oriented-middleware] The MQ Telemetry Transport (MQTT) is an ISO standard (ISO/IEC PRF 20922) supported by the OASIS organization.
[src:dds-protocol/message-oriented-middleware] It provides a lightweight publish/subscribe reliable messaging transport protocol on top of TCP/IP suitable for communication in M2M/IoT contexts where a small code footprint is required and/or network bandwidth is at a premium.
[src:dds-protocol/message-oriented-middleware] The Object Management Group's Data Distribution Service (DDS) provides message-oriented Publish/Subscribe (P/S) middleware standard that aims to enable scalable, real-time, dependable, high-performance and interoperable data exchanges between publishers and subscribers.
[src:dds-protocol/message-oriented-middleware] The standard provides interfaces to C++, C++11, C, Ada, Java, and Ruby.
[src:dds-protocol/message-oriented-middleware] The eXtensible Messaging and Presence Protocol (XMPP) is a communications protocol for message-oriented middleware based on Extensible Markup Language (XML).
[src:dds-protocol/message-oriented-middleware] Designed to be extensible, the protocol has also been used for publish-subscribe systems, signalling for VoIP, video, file transfer, gaming, Internet of Things applications such as the smart grid, and social networking services.
[src:dds-protocol/message-oriented-middleware] Unlike most instant messaging protocols, XMPP is defined in an open standard and uses an open systems approach of development and application, by which anyone may implement an XMPP service and interoperate with other organizations' implementations.
[src:dds-protocol/message-oriented-middleware] Because XMPP is an open protocol, implementations can be developed using any software license; although many server, client, and library implementations are distributed as free and open-source software, many freeware and proprietary software implementations also exist.
[src:dds-protocol/message-oriented-middleware] The Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) formed an XMPP working group in 2002 to formalize the core protocols as an IETF instant messaging and presence technology.
[src:dds-protocol/message-oriented-middleware] The XMPP Working group produced four specifications (RFC 3920, RFC 3921, RFC 3922, RFC 3923), which were approved as Proposed Standards in 2004.
[src:dds-protocol/message-oriented-middleware] In 2011, RFC 3920 and RFC 3921 were superseded by RFC 6120 and RFC 6121 respectively, with RFC 6122 specifying the XMPP address format.
[src:dds-protocol/message-oriented-middleware] In addition to these core protocols standardized at the IETF, the XMPP Standards Foundation (formerly Jabber Software Foundation) is active in developing open XMPP extensions.
[src:dds-protocol/message-oriented-middleware] XMPP-based software is deployed widely across the Internet, according to the XMPP Standards Foundation, and forms the basis for the Department of Defense (DoD) Unified Capabilities Framework.
[src:dds-protocol/message-oriented-middleware] A similar effort is with the actively evolving OpenMAMA project, which aims to provide a common API, especially to C clients.
[src:dds-protocol/message-oriented-middleware] As of August 2012, it is mainly appropriate for distributing market-oriented data (e.g. stock quotes) over pub-sub middleware.
[src:dds-protocol/message-oriented-middleware] Message queues allow the exchange of information between distributed applications.
[src:dds-protocol/message-oriented-middleware] A message queue can reside in memory or disk storage.
[src:dds-protocol/message-oriented-middleware] Messages stay in the queue until the time they are processed by a service consumer.
[src:dds-protocol/message-oriented-middleware] Through the message queue, the application can be implemented independently - they do not need to know each other's position, or continue to implement procedures to remove the need for waiting to receive this message.
[src:dds-protocol/message-passing] In computer science, **message passing** is a technique for invoking behavior (i.e., running a program) on a computer.
[src:dds-protocol/message-passing] The invoking program sends a message to a process (which may be an actor or object) and relies on that process and its supporting infrastructure to then select and run some appropriate code.
[src:dds-protocol/message-passing] Message passing differs from conventional programming where a process, subroutine, or function is directly invoked by name.
[src:dds-protocol/message-passing] Message passing is key to some models of concurrency and object-oriented programming.
[src:dds-protocol/message-passing] Message passing is ubiquitous in modern computer software.
[src:dds-protocol/message-passing] It is used as a way for the objects that make up a program to work with each other and as a means for objects and systems running on different computers (e.g., the Internet) to interact.
[src:dds-protocol/message-passing] Message passing may be implemented by various mechanisms, including channels.
[src:dds-protocol/message-passing] Message passing is a technique for invoking behavior (i.e., running a program) on a computer.
[src:dds-protocol/message-passing] In contrast to the traditional technique of calling a program by name, message passing uses an object model to distinguish the general function from the specific implementations.
[src:dds-protocol/message-passing] The invoking program sends a message and relies on the object to select and execute the appropriate code.
[src:dds-protocol/message-passing] The justifications for using an intermediate layer essentially falls into two categories: encapsulation and distribution.
[src:dds-protocol/message-passing] Message passing is a core technique used for communication between processes, threads, objects, or nodes in both concurrent and distributed systems.
[src:dds-protocol/message-passing] It enables software components to exchange information without sharing memory, often using communication channels, buffers, or middleware to transport messages between senders and receivers.
[src:dds-protocol/message-passing] In some models, message passing can be implemented synchronously, where the sender waits for a reply, or asynchronously, where messages are queued for later processing.
[src:dds-protocol/message-passing] Encapsulation is the idea that software objects should be able to invoke services on other objects without knowing or caring about how those services are implemented.
[src:dds-protocol/message-passing] Encapsulation can reduce the amount of coding logic and make systems more maintainable.
[src:dds-protocol/message-passing] E.g., rather than having IF-THEN statements that determine which subroutine or function to call, a developer can just send a message to the object and the object will select the appropriate code based on its type.
[src:dds-protocol/message-passing] One of the first examples of how this can be used was in the domain of computer graphics.
[src:dds-protocol/message-passing] There are various complexities involved in manipulating graphic objects.
[src:dds-protocol/message-passing] For example, simply using the right formula to compute the area of an enclosed shape will vary depending on if the shape is a triangle, rectangle, ellipse, or circle.
[src:dds-protocol/message-passing] In traditional computer programming, this would result in long IF-THEN statements testing what sort of object the shape was and calling the appropriate code.
[src:dds-protocol/message-passing] The object-oriented way to handle this is to define a class called `Shape` with subclasses such as `Rectangle` and `Ellipse` (which, in turn, have subclasses `Square` and `Circle`) and then to simply send a message to any `Shape` asking it to compute its area.
[src:dds-protocol/message-passing] Each `Shape` object will then invoke the subclass's method with the formula appropriate for that kind of object.
[src:dds-protocol/message-passing] Distributed message passing provides developers with a layer of the architecture that provides common services to build systems made up of sub-systems that run on disparate computers in different locations and at different times.
[src:dds-protocol/message-passing] Synchronous message passing occurs between objects that are running at the same time.
[src:dds-protocol/message-passing] It is used by object-oriented programming languages such as Java and Smalltalk.
[src:dds-protocol/message-passing] Synchronous messaging is analogous to a synchronous function call; just as the function caller waits until the function completes, the sending process waits until the receiving process accepts the message.
[src:dds-protocol/message-passing] This can make synchronous communication unworkable for some applications.
[src:dds-protocol/message-passing] For example, large, distributed systems may not perform well enough to be usable.
[src:dds-protocol/message-passing] Such large, distributed systems may need to operate while some of their subsystems are down for maintenance, etc.
[src:dds-protocol/message-passing] Imagine a busy business office having 100 desktop computers that send emails to each other using synchronous message passing exclusively.
[src:dds-protocol/message-passing] One worker turning off their computer can cause the other 99 computers to freeze until the worker turns their computer back on to process a single email.
[src:dds-protocol/message-passing] Message passing systems can be broadly categorized based on how send and receive operations interact with executing processes.
[src:dds-protocol/message-passing] In **synchronous** message passing, the sending process may block until the receiver has accepted the message, ensuring tight coordination.
[src:dds-protocol/message-passing] In **asynchronous** models, the sender continues execution after sending a message, and messages are typically stored in a queue or buffer until the receiving process retrieves them.
[src:dds-protocol/message-passing] With asynchronous message passing the receiving object can be down or busy when the requesting object sends the message.
[src:dds-protocol/message-passing] Continuing the function call analogy, it is like a function call that returns immediately, without waiting for the called function to complete.
[src:dds-protocol/message-passing] Messages are sent to a queue where they are stored until the receiving process requests them.
[src:dds-protocol/message-passing] The receiving process processes its messages and sends results to a queue for pickup by the original process (or some designated next process).
[src:dds-protocol/message-passing] Asynchronous messaging requires additional capabilities for storing and retransmitting data for systems that may not run concurrently, and are generally handled by an intermediary level of software (often called middleware); a common type being Message-oriented middleware (MOM).
[src:dds-protocol/message-passing] The buffer required in asynchronous communication can cause problems when it is full.
[src:dds-protocol/message-passing] A decision has to be made whether to block the sender or whether to discard future messages.
[src:dds-protocol/message-passing] If messages are dropped, communication is no longer reliable.
[src:dds-protocol/message-passing] Synchronous communication can be built on top of asynchronous communication by using a Synchronizer.
[src:dds-protocol/message-passing] For example, the α-Synchronizer works by ensuring that the sender always waits for an acknowledgement message from the receiver.
[src:dds-protocol/message-passing] The sender only sends the next message after the acknowledgement has been received.
[src:dds-protocol/message-passing] On the other hand, asynchronous communication can also be built on top of synchronous communication.
[src:dds-protocol/message-passing] For example, modern microkernels generally only provide a synchronous messaging primitive and asynchronous messaging can be implemented on top by using helper threads.
[src:dds-protocol/message-passing] Message-passing systems use either distributed or local objects.
[src:dds-protocol/message-passing] With distributed objects the sender and receiver may be on different computers, running different operating systems, using different programming languages, etc.
[src:dds-protocol/message-passing] In this case the bus layer takes care of details about converting data from one system to another, sending and receiving data across the network, etc.
[src:dds-protocol/message-passing] The Remote Procedure Call (RPC) protocol in Unix was an early example of this.
[src:dds-protocol/message-passing] With this type of message passing it is not a requirement that sender nor receiver use object-oriented programming.
[src:dds-protocol/message-passing] Procedural language systems can be wrapped and treated as large grained objects capable of sending and receiving messages.
[src:dds-protocol/message-passing] Examples of systems that support distributed objects are: Emerald, ONC RPC, CORBA, Java RMI, DCOM, SOAP, .NET Remoting, CTOS, QNX Neutrino RTOS, OpenBinder and D-Bus.
[src:dds-protocol/message-passing] Distributed object systems have been called "shared nothing" systems because the message passing abstraction hides underlying state changes that may be used in the implementation of sending messages.
[src:dds-protocol/message-passing] Distributed, or asynchronous, message-passing has additional overhead compared to calling a procedure.
[src:dds-protocol/message-passing] In message-passing, arguments must be copied to the new message.
[src:dds-protocol/message-passing] Some arguments can contain megabytes of data, all of which must be copied and transmitted to the receiving object.
[src:dds-protocol/message-passing] Traditional procedure calls differ from message-passing in terms of memory usage, transfer time and locality.
[src:dds-protocol/message-passing] Arguments are passed to the receiver typically by general-purpose registers requiring no additional storage nor transfer time, or in a parameter list containing the arguments' addresses (a few bits).
[src:dds-protocol/message-passing] Address-passing is not possible for distributed systems since the systems use separate address spaces.
[src:dds-protocol/message-passing] Web browsers and web servers are examples of processes that communicate by message-passing.
[src:dds-protocol/message-passing] A URL is an example of referencing a resource without exposing process internals.
[src:dds-protocol/message-passing] A subroutine call or method invocation will not exit until the invoked computation has terminated.
[src:dds-protocol/message-passing] Asynchronous message-passing, by contrast, can result in a response arriving a significant time after the request message was sent.
[src:dds-protocol/message-passing] A message-handler will, in general, process messages from more than one sender.
[src:dds-protocol/message-passing] This means its state can change for reasons unrelated to the behavior of a single sender or client process.
[src:dds-protocol/message-passing] This is in contrast to the typical behavior of an object upon which methods are being invoked: the latter is expected to remain in the same state between method invocations.
[src:dds-protocol/message-passing] In other words, the message-handler behaves analogously to a volatile object.
[src:dds-protocol/message-passing] The prominent mathematical models of message passing are the Actor model and Pi calculus.
[src:dds-protocol/message-passing] In mathematical terms a message is the single means to pass control to an object.
[src:dds-protocol/message-passing] If the object responds to the message, it has a method for that message.
[src:dds-protocol/message-passing] Alan Kay has argued that message passing is more important than objects in OOP, and that objects themselves are often over-emphasized.
[src:dds-protocol/message-passing] The live distributed objects programming model builds upon this observation; it uses the concept of a distributed data flow to characterize the behavior of a complex distributed system in terms of message patterns, using high-level, functional-style specifications.
[src:dds-protocol/object-management-group] The **Object Management Group** (**OMG**) is a computer industry *standards development organization* (SDO), or *voluntary consensus standards body* (VCSB).
[src:dds-protocol/object-management-group] OMG develops enterprise integration and modeling standards for a range of technologies.
[src:dds-protocol/object-management-group] The goal of the OMG was a common portable and interoperable object model with methods and data that work using all types of development environments on all types of platforms.
[src:dds-protocol/object-management-group] The group provides only specifications, not implementations.
[src:dds-protocol/object-management-group] But before a specification can be accepted as a standard by the group, the members of the submitter team must guarantee that they will bring a conforming product to market within a year.
[src:dds-protocol/object-management-group] This is an attempt to prevent unimplemented (and unimplementable) technical standards.
[src:dds-protocol/object-management-group] Other private companies or open source groups are encouraged to produce conforming products and OMG is attempting to develop mechanisms to enforce true interoperability.
[src:dds-protocol/object-management-group] OMG hosts four technical meetings per year for its members and interested nonmembers.
[src:dds-protocol/object-management-group] The Technical Meetings provide a neutral forum to discuss, develop and adopt standards that enable software interoperability.
[src:dds-protocol/object-management-group] Founded in 1989 by eleven companies (including Hewlett-Packard, IBM, Sun Microsystems, Apple Computer, American Airlines, iGrafx, and Data General), OMG's initial focus was to create a heterogeneous distributed object standard.
[src:dds-protocol/object-management-group] The founding executive team included Christopher Stone and John Slitz.
[src:dds-protocol/object-management-group] Current leadership includes chairman and CEO Bill Hoffman and Technical Director Mike Bennett.
[src:dds-protocol/object-management-group] Richard Soley, who led OMG from its creation onwards and was its Chairman and President, died in 2023.
[src:dds-protocol/object-management-group] Since 2000, the group's international headquarters has been located in Boston, Massachusetts; however, OMG's corporate office is now virtual.
[src:dds-protocol/object-management-group] OMG is a standards development organization which technical work is accomplished by Task Forces, Special Interest Groups, and an Architecture Board (Structure and Governance).
[src:dds-protocol/object-management-group] Over OMG's history, its members have defined more than 200 standard specifications.
[src:dds-protocol/object-management-group] A few of the most widely known OMG standards are mentioned below.
[src:dds-protocol/object-management-group] Of the many standards maintained by the OMG, 13 have been ratified as International Organization for Standardization (ISO) standards.
[src:dds-protocol/object-management-group] Historically, there were packages `org.omg.*` in Java and its standard library named the Java Class Library.
[src:dds-protocol/object-management-group] These have since been deprecated in Java 9 and removed in Java 11.
[src:dds-protocol/publish-subscribe-pattern] In software architecture, the **publish–subscribe pattern** (**pub/sub**) is a messaging pattern in which message senders, called **publishers**, categorize messages into classes (or *topics*), and send them without needing to know which components will receive them.
[src:dds-protocol/publish-subscribe-pattern] Message recipients, called **subscribers**, express interest in one or more classes and only receive messages in those classes, without needing to know the identity of the publishers.
[src:dds-protocol/publish-subscribe-pattern] This pattern decouples the components that produce messages from those that consume them, and supports asynchronous, many-to-many communication.
[src:dds-protocol/publish-subscribe-pattern] The publish–subscribe model is commonly contrasted with message queue-based and point-to-point messaging models, where producers send messages directly to consumers.
[src:dds-protocol/publish-subscribe-pattern] Publish–subscribe is a sibling of the message queue paradigm, and is typically a component of larger message-oriented middleware systems.
[src:dds-protocol/publish-subscribe-pattern] Many modern messaging frameworks and protocols, such as the Java Message Service (JMS), Apache Kafka, and MQTT, support both the pub/sub and queue-based models.
[src:dds-protocol/publish-subscribe-pattern] This pattern provides greater network scalability and supports more dynamic topologies, but can make it harder to modify the publisher’s logic or the structure of the published data.
[src:dds-protocol/publish-subscribe-pattern] Compared to synchronous patterns like RPC and point-to-point messaging, publish–subscribe provides the highest level of decoupling among architectural components.
[src:dds-protocol/publish-subscribe-pattern] However, it can also lead to semantic or format coupling between publishers and subscribers, which may cause systems to become entangled or brittle over time.
[src:dds-protocol/publish-subscribe-pattern] In publish–subscribe systems, subscribers typically receive only a subset of messages.
[src:dds-protocol/publish-subscribe-pattern] In most pub/sub systems, publishers and subscribers communicate through a central intermediary such as a message broker or event bus.
[src:dds-protocol/publish-subscribe-pattern] The broker receives messages from publishers and forwards them to the appropriate subscribers, optionally performing store and forward, priority queuing, or other routing logic.
[src:dds-protocol/publish-subscribe-pattern] Some pub/sub systems use **brokerless** architectures, in which publishers and subscribers discover each other and exchange messages directly.
[src:dds-protocol/publish-subscribe-pattern] For example, the Data Distribution Service (DDS) middleware uses IP multicast and metadata sharing to establish communication paths.
[src:dds-protocol/publish-subscribe-pattern] Brokerless systems require construction of overlay networks, often using Small-World topologies to enable efficient routing.
[src:dds-protocol/publish-subscribe-pattern] It was shown by Jon Kleinberg that efficient decentralized routing requires Navigable Small-World topologies, which are employed in federated or peer-to-peer pub/sub systems.
[src:dds-protocol/publish-subscribe-pattern] Locality-aware pub/sub networks use low-latency links to reduce message propagation time.
[src:dds-protocol/publish-subscribe-pattern] One of the earliest publicly described pub/sub systems was the "news" subsystem of the Isis Toolkit, presented at the 1987 ACM Symposium on Operating Systems Principles (SOSP '87).
[src:dds-protocol/publish-subscribe-pattern] As distributed systems became more common, the publish–subscribe model evolved to emphasize asynchronous messaging and broker-mediated communication, setting it apart from the more tightly coupled observer pattern.
[src:dds-protocol/publish-subscribe-pattern] Publishers are loosely coupled to subscribers, and need not even know of their existence.
[src:dds-protocol/publish-subscribe-pattern] With the topic being the focus, publishers and subscribers are allowed to remain ignorant of system topology.
[src:dds-protocol/publish-subscribe-pattern] Each can continue to operate as per normal independently of the other.
[src:dds-protocol/publish-subscribe-pattern] In the traditional tightly coupled client–server paradigm, the client cannot post messages to the server while the server process is not running, nor can the server receive messages unless the client is running.
[src:dds-protocol/publish-subscribe-pattern] Many pub/sub systems decouple not only the locations of the publishers and subscribers but also decouple them temporally.
[src:dds-protocol/publish-subscribe-pattern] A common strategy used by middleware analysts with such pub/sub systems is to take down a publisher to allow the subscriber to work through the backlog (a form of bandwidth throttling).
[src:dds-protocol/publish-subscribe-pattern] Pub/sub provides the opportunity for better scalability than traditional client-server, through parallel operation, message caching, tree-based or network-based routing, etc.
[src:dds-protocol/publish-subscribe-pattern] Outside of the enterprise environment, on the other hand, the pub/sub paradigm has proven its scalability to volumes far beyond those of a single data center, providing Internet-wide distributed messaging through web syndication protocols such as RSS and Atom.
[src:dds-protocol/publish-subscribe-pattern] These syndication protocols accept higher latency and lack of delivery guarantees in exchange for the ability for even a low-end web server to syndicate messages to (potentially) millions of separate subscriber nodes.
[src:dds-protocol/publish-subscribe-pattern] Redundant subscribers in a pub/sub system can help assure message delivery with minimal additional complexity.
[src:dds-protocol/publish-subscribe-pattern] For example, a factory may utilize a pub/sub system where equipment can publish problems or failures to a subscriber that displays and logs those problems.
[src:dds-protocol/publish-subscribe-pattern] If the logger fails (crashes), equipment problem publishers won't necessarily receive notice of the logger failure, and error messages will not be displayed or recorded by any equipment on the pub/sub system.
[src:dds-protocol/publish-subscribe-pattern] In a client/server system, when an error logger fails, the system will receive an indication of the error logger (server) failure.
[src:dds-protocol/publish-subscribe-pattern] However, the client/server system will have to deal with that failure by having redundant logging servers online, or by dynamically spawning fallback logging servers.
[src:dds-protocol/publish-subscribe-pattern] This adds complexity to the client and server designs, as well as to the client/server architecture as a whole.
[src:dds-protocol/publish-subscribe-pattern] In a pub/sub system, redundant logging subscribers that are exact duplicates of the existing logger can be added to the system to increase logging reliability without any impact to any other equipment on the system.
[src:dds-protocol/publish-subscribe-pattern] The feature of assured error message logging can also be added incrementally, subsequent to implementing the basic functionality of equipment problem message logging.
[src:dds-protocol/publish-subscribe-pattern] The most serious problems with pub/sub systems are a side-effect of their main advantage: the decoupling of publisher from subscriber.
[src:dds-protocol/publish-subscribe-pattern] A pub/sub system must be designed carefully to be able to provide stronger system properties that a particular application might require, such as assured delivery.
[src:dds-protocol/publish-subscribe-pattern] The pub/sub pattern scales well for small networks with a small number of publisher and subscriber nodes and low message volume.
[src:dds-protocol/publish-subscribe-pattern] However, as the number of nodes and messages grows, the likelihood of instabilities increases, limiting the maximum scalability of a pub/sub network.
[src:dds-protocol/publish-subscribe-pattern] For pub/sub systems that use brokers (servers), the argument for a broker to send messages to a subscriber is in-band, and can be subject to security problems.
[src:dds-protocol/publish-subscribe-pattern] Brokers might be fooled into sending notifications to the wrong client, amplifying denial of service requests against the client.
[src:dds-protocol/publish-subscribe-pattern] Brokers themselves could be overloaded as they allocate resources to track created subscriptions.
[src:dds-protocol/publish-subscribe-pattern] Even with systems that do not rely on brokers, a subscriber might be able to receive data that it is not authorized to receive.
[src:dds-protocol/publish-subscribe-pattern] An unauthorized publisher may be able to introduce incorrect or damaging messages into the pub/sub system.
[src:dds-protocol/publish-subscribe-pattern] This is especially true with systems that broadcast or multicast their messages.
[src:dds-protocol/publish-subscribe-pattern] Transport Layer Security (SSL/TLS)) can prevent unauthorized access, but cannot prevent damaging messages from being introduced by authorized publishers.
[src:dds-protocol/publish-subscribe-pattern] Architectures other than pub/sub, such as client/server systems, are also vulnerable to authorized message senders that behave maliciously.
[src:dds-protocol/real-time-computing] The term "real-time" is also used in simulation to mean that the simulation's clock runs at the same speed as a real clock.
[src:dds-protocol/real-time-computing] Real-time responses are often understood to be in the order of milliseconds, and sometimes microseconds.
[src:dds-protocol/real-time-computing] A system not specified as operating in real time cannot usually *guarantee* a response within any timeframe, although *typical* or *expected* response times may be given.
[src:dds-protocol/real-time-computing] Real-time processing *fails* if not completed within a specified deadline relative to an event; deadlines must always be met, regardless of system load.
[src:dds-protocol/real-time-computing] A real-time system has been described as one which "controls an environment by receiving data, processing them, and returning the results sufficiently quickly to affect the environment at that time".
[src:dds-protocol/real-time-computing] The term "real-time" is used in process control and enterprise systems to mean "without significant delay".
[src:dds-protocol/real-time-computing] Real-time software may use one or more of the following: synchronous programming languages, real-time operating systems (RTOSes), and real-time networks.
[src:dds-protocol/real-time-computing] Each of these provides essential frameworks on which to build a real-time software application.
[src:dds-protocol/real-time-computing] Systems used for many safety-critical applications must be real-time, such as for control of fly-by-wire aircraft, or anti-lock brakes, both of which demand immediate and accurate mechanical response.
[src:dds-protocol/real-time-computing] The term *real-time* derives from its use in early simulation, where a real-world process is simulated at a rate which matched that of the real process (now called real-time simulation to avoid ambiguity).
[src:dds-protocol/real-time-computing] Analog computers, most often, were capable of simulating at a much faster pace than real-time, a situation that could be just as dangerous as a slow simulation if it were not also recognized and accounted for.
[src:dds-protocol/real-time-computing] Minicomputers, particularly from the 1970s onwards, when built into dedicated embedded systems such as DOG (digital on-screen graphic) scanners, increased the need for low-latency priority-driven responses to important interactions with incoming data.
[src:dds-protocol/real-time-computing] Operating systems such as Data General's RDOS (Real-Time Disk Operating System) and RTOS with background and foreground scheduling as well as Digital Equipment Corporation's RT-11 date from this era.
[src:dds-protocol/real-time-computing] Background-foreground scheduling allowed low-priority tasks CPU time when no foreground task needed to execute, and gave absolute priority within the foreground to threads/tasks with the highest priority.
[src:dds-protocol/real-time-computing] Real-time operating systems would also be used for time-sharing multiuser duties.
[src:dds-protocol/real-time-computing] For example, Data General Business Basic could run in the foreground or background of RDOS and would introduce additional elements to the scheduling algorithm to make it more appropriate for people interacting via dumb terminals.
[src:dds-protocol/real-time-computing] Early personal computers were sometimes used for real-time computing.
[src:dds-protocol/real-time-computing] The possibility of deactivating other interrupts allowed for hard-coded loops with defined timing, and the low interrupt latency allowed the implementation of a real-time operating system, giving the user interface and the disk drives lower priority than the real-time thread.
[src:dds-protocol/real-time-computing] However, several coding libraries exist that offer real-time capabilities in a high-level language on a variety of operating systems, for example, Real-time Java.
[src:dds-protocol/real-time-computing] Later microprocessors such as the Motorola 68000 and subsequent family members (68010, 68020, ColdFire, etc.) also became popular with manufacturers of industrial control systems.
[src:dds-protocol/real-time-computing] This application area is one where real-time control offers genuine advantages in terms of process performance and safety.
[src:dds-protocol/real-time-computing] A system is said to be *real-time* if the total correctness of an operation depends not only upon its logical correctness, but also upon the time in which it is performed.
[src:dds-protocol/real-time-computing] Thus, the goal of a *hard real-time system* is to ensure that all deadlines are met, but for *soft real-time systems* the goal becomes meeting a certain subset of deadlines in order to optimize some application-specific criteria.
[src:dds-protocol/real-time-computing] The particular criteria optimized depend on the application, but some typical examples include maximizing the number of deadlines met, minimizing the lateness of tasks and maximizing the number of high-priority tasks meeting their deadlines.
[src:dds-protocol/real-time-computing] In the context of multitasking systems the scheduling policy is normally priority driven (pre-emptive schedulers).
[src:dds-protocol/real-time-computing] In some situations, these can guarantee hard real-time performance (for instance, if the set of tasks and their priorities is known in advance).
[src:dds-protocol/real-time-computing] There are other hard real-time schedulers such as rate-monotonic, which is not common in general-purpose systems, as it requires additional information in order to schedule a task: namely, a bound or worst-case estimate for how long the task must execute.
[src:dds-protocol/real-time-computing] Specific algorithms for scheduling such hard real-time tasks exist, like earliest deadline first, which, ignoring the overhead of context switching, is sufficient for system loads of less than 100%.
[src:dds-protocol/real-time-computing] New overlay scheduling systems, such as an adaptive partition scheduler assist in managing large systems with a mixture of hard real-time and non real-time applications.
[src:dds-protocol/real-time-computing] In a real-time digital signal processing (DSP) process, the analyzed (input) and generated (output) samples can be processed (or generated) continuously in the time it takes to input and output the same set of samples *independent* of the processing delay.
[src:dds-protocol/real-time-computing] It means that the processing delay must be bounded even if the processing continues for an unlimited time.
[src:dds-protocol/real-time-computing] The mean processing time per sample, including overhead, is no greater than the sampling period, which is the reciprocal of the sampling rate.
[src:dds-protocol/real-time-computing] This is the criterion whether the samples are grouped together in large segments and processed as blocks or are processed individually and whether there are long, short, or non-existent input and output buffers.
[src:dds-protocol/real-time-computing] Consider an audio DSP example; if a process requires 2.01 seconds to analyze, synthesize, or process 2.00 seconds of sound, it is not real-time.
[src:dds-protocol/real-time-computing] However, if it takes 1.99 seconds, it is or can be made into a real-time DSP process.
[src:dds-protocol/real-time-computing] A common life analogy is standing in a line or queue waiting for the checkout in a grocery store.
[src:dds-protocol/real-time-computing] If the line asymptotically grows longer and longer without bound, the checkout process is not real-time.
[src:dds-protocol/real-time-computing] If the length of the line is bounded, customers are being "processed" and output as rapidly, on average, as they are being inputted, then that process *is* real-time.
[src:dds-protocol/real-time-computing] The grocer might go out of business or must at least lose business if they cannot make their checkout process real-time; thus, it is fundamentally important that this process is real-time.
[src:dds-protocol/real-time-computing] A signal processing algorithm that cannot keep up with the flow of input data, with output falling further and further behind the input, is not real-time.
[src:dds-protocol/real-time-computing] If the delay of the output (relative to the input) is bounded regarding a process that operates over an unlimited time, then that signal processing algorithm is real-time, even if the throughput delay may be very long.
[src:dds-protocol/real-time-computing] Real-time signal processing is necessary, but not sufficient in and of itself, for live signal processing such as what is required in live event support.
[src:dds-protocol/real-time-computing] Live audio digital signal processing requires both real-time operation and a sufficient limit to throughput delay so as to be tolerable to performers using stage monitors or in-ear monitors and not noticeable as lip sync error by the audience also directly watching the performers.
[src:dds-protocol/real-time-computing] Tolerable limits to latency for live, real-time processing is a subject of investigation and debate, but is estimated to be between 6 and 20 milliseconds.
[src:dds-protocol/real-time-computing] Real-time bidirectional telecommunications delays of less than 300 ms ("round trip" or twice the unidirectional delay) are considered "acceptable" to avoid undesired "talk-over" in conversation.
[src:dds-protocol/real-time-computing] Real-time computing is sometimes misunderstood to be high-performance computing, but this is not an accurate classification.
[src:dds-protocol/real-time-computing] For example, a massive supercomputer executing a scientific simulation may offer impressive performance, yet it is not executing a real-time computation.
[src:dds-protocol/real-time-computing] Conversely, once the hardware and software for an anti-lock braking system have been designed to meet its required deadlines, no further performance gains are obligatory or even useful.
[src:dds-protocol/real-time-computing] Furthermore, if a network server is highly loaded with network traffic, its response time may be slower, but will (in most cases) still succeed before it times out (hits its deadline).
[src:dds-protocol/real-time-computing] Hence, such a network server would not be considered a real-time system: temporal failures (delays, time-outs, etc.) are typically small and compartmentalized (limited in effect), but are not catastrophic failures.
[src:dds-protocol/real-time-computing] In a real-time system, such as the FTSE 100 Index, a slowdown beyond limits would often be considered catastrophic in its application context.
[src:dds-protocol/real-time-computing] The most important requirement of a real-time system is consistent output, not high throughput.
[src:dds-protocol/real-time-computing] Some kinds of software, such as many chess-playing programs, can fall into either category.
[src:dds-protocol/real-time-computing] For instance, a chess program designed to play in a tournament with a clock will need to decide on a move before a certain deadline or lose the game, and is therefore a real-time computation, but a chess program that is allowed to run indefinitely before moving is not.
[src:dds-protocol/real-time-computing] In both of these cases, however, high performance is desirable: the more work a tournament chess program can do in the allotted time, the better its moves will be, and the faster an unconstrained chess program runs, the sooner it will be able to move.
[src:dds-protocol/real-time-computing] High performance is indicative of the amount of processing that is performed in a given amount of time, whereas real-time is the ability to get done with the processing to yield a useful output in the available time.
[src:dds-protocol/real-time-computing] For example, a near-real-time display depicts an event or situation as it existed at the current time minus the processing time, as nearly the time of the live event.
[src:dds-protocol/real-time-computing] The distinction between the terms "near real time" and "real time" is somewhat nebulous and must be defined for the situation at hand.
[src:dds-protocol/real-time-computing] The term implies that there are no significant delays.
[src:dds-protocol/real-time-computing] In many cases, processing described as "real-time" would be more accurately described as "near real-time".
[src:dds-protocol/real-time-computing] Near real-time also refers to delayed real-time transmission of voice and video.
[src:dds-protocol/real-time-computing] It allows playing video images, in approximately real-time, without having to wait for an entire large video file to download.
[src:dds-protocol/real-time-computing] Incompatible databases can export/import to common flat files that the other database can import/export on a scheduled basis so they can sync/share common data in "near real-time" with each other.
[src:dds-protocol/real-time-computing] Several methods exist to aid the design of real-time systems, an example of which is MASCOT, an old but very successful method that represents the concurrent structure of the system.
[src:dds-protocol/real-time-computing] Other examples are HOOD, Real-Time UML, AADL, the Ravenscar profile, and Real-time Java.
